{"text": "UFourier \u22971\n\n(54.14)\n\nThe first stage is a unitary operation UH that sets the x register in a democratic state. It can realized by operating\n\non \u03a8 with the Hadamard gate. Disregarding normalization we get \u03a8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\nx x\u27e9\u2297 y=1\u27e9\n\n(54.15)\n\n286\n\nThe second stage is an x controlled operation UM. This stage is formally like a quantum measurement: The x register\n\nis \u201dmeasured\u201d by the y register. The result is \u03a8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\nx x\u27e9\u2297 y=f(x)\u27e9\n\n(54.16)\n\nNow the y register is entangled with the x register. The fourth stage is to perform Fourier transform on the x register: \u03a8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\nx\n\n\"X\n\nx\u2032\n\nei 2\u03c0\n\nNc xx\u2032 x\u2032\u27e9\n\n#\n\n\u2297 f(x)\u27e9\n\n(54.17)\n\nWe replace the dummy integer index x\u2032 by k = (2\u03c0/Nc)x\u2032 and re-write the result as \u03a8\u27e9\n\n=\n\nX\n\nk k\u27e9\u2297\n\n\"X\n\nx\n\neikx f(x)\u27e9\n\n#\n\n\u2261\n\nX\n\nk\n\npk k\u27e9\u2297 \u03c7(k)\u27e9\n\n(54.18)\n\nThe final stage is to measure the x register. The probability to get k as the result is\n\npk\n\n=\n\nX\n\nx\n\neikx f(x)\u27e9\n\n2\n\n(54.19)\n\nThe only non-zero probabilities are associated with k = integer \u00d7 (2\u03c0/r). Thus we are likely to find one of these k\n\nvalues, from which we can deduce the period r. Ideally the error is associated with the finite length of the x register.\n\nBy making the x register larger the visibility of the Fourier components becomes better.\n\n====== [54.4] Single qubit quantum gates\n\nThe simplest gates are one quibit gates. They can be regarded as spin rotations. Let us list some of them:\n\nT =\n\n\u0012 1\n\n0\n\n0 ei\u03c0/4\n\n\u0013\n\n(54.20)\n\nS = T 2 =\n\n\u0012\n\n1 0\n\n0 i\n\n\u0013\n\nZ = S2 =\n\n\u0012\n\n1\n\n0\n\n0 \u22121\n\n\u0013\n\n= \u03c3z = ie\u2212i\u03c0Sz\n\nX =\n\n\u0012\n\n0 1\n\n1 0\n\n\u0013\n\n= \u03c3x = ie\u2212i\u03c0Sx = NOT gate\n\nY\n\n=\n\n\u0012\n\n0 \u2212i\n\ni\n\n0\n\n\u0013\n\n= \u03c3y = ie\u2212i\u03c0Sy = iR2\n\nH =\n\n1\n\n\u221a\n\n2\n\n\u0012\n\n1\n\n1\n\n1 \u22121\n\n\u0013\n\n=\n\n1\n\n\u221a\n\n2(\u03c3x + \u03c3z) = ie\u2212i\u03c0Sn = Hadamard gate\n\nR =\n\n1\n\n\u221a\n\n2\n\n\u0012\n\n1 \u22121\n\n1\n\n1\n\n\u0013\n\n=\n\n1\n\n\u221a\n\n2(1 \u2212i\u03c3y) = e\u2212i(\u03c0/2)Sy = 90deg Rotation\n\nWe have R4 = \u22121 which is a 2\u03c0 rotation in SU(2). We have X2 = Y 2 = Z2 = H2 = 1 which implies that these are \u03c0\n\nrotations in U(2).", "embedding": [5.625571e-05, -0.031043686, 0.033347066, -0.011748696, -0.025541931, -0.022020893, -0.0367353, -0.024431985, -0.074234, 0.09529714, 0.037121125, 0.031598397, -0.006711924, -0.045033716, -0.01834345, 0.019958558, -0.0051513338, -0.036807578, -0.054524258, 0.013114659, 0.04705709, -0.027940378, -0.085012935, 0.0046755825, -0.030287115, 0.02328022, 0.008465903, 0.004971997, 0.03387497, 0.06709877, 0.003741063, -0.009950319, 0.06446898, -0.028955976, -0.03353884, -0.00072070817, 0.025585365, -0.023468863, -0.009219454, -0.03130044, 0.0049097277, 0.02071835, 0.0076742093, -0.008932916, -0.071723044, -0.030189909, -0.045796767, -0.013766277, -0.0053536533, -0.05510461, -0.024128253, -0.01154738, 0.022005508, -0.035266675, -0.025798338, 0.0052438998, 0.022327034, 0.0031029836, -0.04399052, 0.00911645, 0.044191986, -0.01288798, 0.0051732096, -0.069777235, 0.04903787, 0.017471073, -0.044442825, -0.007138322, 0.012892648, -0.059156466, 0.0042166295, -0.02829112, -0.02706208, -0.042216975, -0.0112053435, 0.010736618, -0.00083189114, 0.006153775, -0.055086073, 0.010544157, -0.0064376215, -0.034630068, -0.022858921, -0.02406154, 0.012034627, 0.012305241, 0.02289243, -0.027533479, -0.030075114, -0.032222725, 0.055886686, 0.03757986, -0.0012430393, 0.010445247, 0.022804905, -0.008141187, 0.020498537, 0.021308122, 0.042402178, -0.004354958, 0.0034201033, 0.051138416, -0.02923435, 0.052320626, -0.017074442, 0.004892138, -0.020490924, 0.055784114, -0.037343785, -0